<doc id="432989" wikidata="Q934370" url="?curid=432989" title="Needham–Schroeder protocol">
<text>The Needham–Schroeder protocol is one of the two key transport protocols intended for use over an insecure network, both proposed by Roger Needham and Michael Schroeder. These are:
* The &quot;Needham–Schroeder Symmetric Key Protocol&quot;, based on a symmetric encryption algorithm. It forms the basis for the Kerberos protocol. This protocol aims to establish a session key between two parties on a network, typically to protect further communication.
* The &quot;Needham–Schroeder Public-Key Protocol&quot;, based on public-key cryptography. This protocol is intended to provide mutual authentication between two parties communicating on a network, but in its proposed form is insecure.

== Symmetric protocol ==
Here, Alice formula_1 initiates the communication to Bob . formula_2 is a server trusted by both parties. In the communication:
* formula_3 and formula_4 are identities of Alice and Bob respectively
* formula_5 is a symmetric key known only to formula_3 and formula_2
* formula_8 is a symmetric key known only to formula_4 and formula_2
* formula_11 and formula_12 are nonces generated by formula_3 and formula_4 respectively
* formula_15 is a symmetric, generated key, which will be the session key of the session between formula_3 and formula_4

The protocol can be specified as follows in security protocol notation:

: formula_18
:: Alice sends a message to the server identifying herself and Bob, telling the server she wants to communicate with Bob.
: formula_19
:: The server generates formula_15 and sends back to Alice a copy encrypted under formula_8 for Alice to forward to Bob and also a copy for Alice. Since Alice may be requesting keys for several different people, the nonce assures Alice that the message is fresh and that the server is replying to that particular message and the inclusion of Bob&#x27;s name tells Alice who she is to share this key with.
: formula_22
:: Alice forwards the key to Bob who can decrypt it with the key he shares with the server, thus authenticating the data.
: formula_23
:: Bob sends Alice a nonce encrypted under formula_15 to show that he has the key.
: formula_25
:: Alice performs a simple operation on the nonce, re-encrypts it and sends it back verifying that she is still alive and that she holds the key.

=== Attacks on the protocol ===
The protocol is vulnerable to a replay attack (as identified by Denning and Sacco). If an attacker uses an older, compromised value for , he can then replay the message formula_26 to Bob, who will accept it, being unable to tell that the key is not fresh.

=== Fixing the attack ===
This flaw is fixed in the Kerberos protocol by the inclusion of a timestamp. It can also be fixed with the use of nonces as described below. At the beginning of the protocol:
: formula_27
:: Alice sends to Bob a request.
: formula_28
:: Bob responds with a nonce encrypted under his key with the Server.
: formula_29
:: Alice sends a message to the server identifying herself and Bob, telling the server she wants to communicate with Bob.
: formula_30
:: Note the inclusion of the nonce.

The protocol then continues as described through the final three steps as described in the original protocol above. Note that formula_31 is a different nonce from . The inclusion of this new nonce prevents the replaying of a compromised version of formula_26 since such a message would need to be of the form formula_33 which the attacker can&#x27;t forge since she does not have .

== Public-key protocol ==
This assumes the use of a public-key encryption algorithm.

Here, Alice formula_1 and Bob formula_35 use a trusted server formula_36 to distribute public keys on request. These keys are:
* formula_37 and , respectively public and private halves of an encryption key-pair belonging to formula_3 (formula_2 stands for &quot;secret key&quot; here)
* formula_40 and , similar belonging to formula_4
* formula_42 and , similar belonging to . (Note that this key-pair will be used for digital signatures, i.e., formula_43 used for signing a message and formula_42 used for verification. formula_42 must be known to formula_3 and formula_4 before the protocol starts.)

The protocol runs as follows:
: formula_48
:: formula_3 requests &#x27;s public keys from .
: formula_50
:: formula_2 responds with public key formula_40 alongside &#x27;s identity, signed by the server for authentication purposes.
: formula_53
:: formula_3 chooses a random formula_11 and sends it to .
: formula_56
:: formula_4 now knows A wants to communicate, so formula_4 requests &#x27;s public keys.
: formula_59
:: Server responds.
: formula_60
:: formula_4 chooses a random , and sends it to formula_3 along with formula_11 to prove ability to decrypt with .
: formula_64
:: formula_3 confirms formula_12 to , to prove ability to decrypt with .

At the end of the protocol, formula_3 and formula_4 know each other&#x27;s identities, and know both formula_11 and . These nonces are not known to eavesdroppers.

=== An attack on the protocol ===
This protocol is vulnerable to a man-in-the-middle attack. If an impostor formula_70 can persuade formula_3 to initiate a session with them, they can relay the messages to formula_4 and convince formula_4 that he is communicating with .

Ignoring the traffic to and from formula_2, which is unchanged, the attack runs as follows:
: formula_75
:: formula_3 sends formula_11 to , who decrypts the message with .
: formula_78
:: formula_70 relays the message to , pretending that formula_3 is communicating.
: formula_81
:: formula_4 sends formula_12.
: formula_84
:: formula_70 relays it to .
: formula_86
:: formula_3 decrypts formula_88 and confirms it to , who learns it.
: formula_89
:: formula_70 re-encrypts , and convinces formula_4 that she&#x27;s decrypted it.

At the end of the attack, formula_4 falsely believes that formula_3 is communicating with him, and that formula_11 and formula_12 are known only to formula_3 and .

The following example illustrates the attack. Alice () would like to contact her bank (). We assume that an impostor () successfully convinces formula_3 that they are the bank. As a consequence, formula_3 uses the public key of formula_70 instead of using the public key of formula_4 to encrypt the messages she intends to send to her bank. Therefore, formula_3 sends formula_70 her nonce encrypted with the public key of . formula_70 decrypts the message using their private key and contacts formula_4 sending it the nonce of formula_3 encrypted with the public key of formula_4. formula_4 has no way to know that this message was actually sent by . formula_4 responds with their own nonce and encrypts the message with the public key of . Since formula_70 is not in possession of the private key of formula_3 they have to relay the message to formula_3 without knowing the content. A decrypts the message with her private key and respond with the nonce of formula_4 encrypted with the public key of . formula_70 decrypts the message using their private key and is now in possession of nonce formula_3 and . Therefore, they can now impersonate the bank and the client respectively.

=== Fixing the man-in-the-middle attack ===
The attack was first described in a 1995 paper by Gavin Lowe.
The paper also describes a fixed version of the scheme, referred to as the Needham–Schroeder–Lowe protocol. The fix involves the modification of message six to include the responder&#x27;s identity, that is we replace:
: formula_60
with the fixed version:
: formula_116
and the intruder cannot successfully replay the message because A is expecting a message containing the identity of I whereas the message will have identity of .

